{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488593","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488593"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:48:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:48:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"486"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"486","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/486"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.06,0.07,0.21,0.63]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"486"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"45044"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"486","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/486"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"486"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29946"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"348"},{"type":"tags","id":"4891"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"980"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1026"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"45044","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/45044"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old man presents after an episode of transient blurring of vision in his right eye. This occurred for ten minutes and descended like a curtain from top to bottom of the visual field, soon followed by his vision returning to normal. This is his third such episode in two months. He has not had any recent jaw claudication, headache or weight loss. He has a regular pulse of 78/min, blood pressure of 132/70mmHg and respiratory rate of 12/min. He has normal eye movements and pupillary reactions. Fundoscopy is shown. Electrocardiogram shows a sinus rhythm. Inflammatory markers including erythrocyte sedimentation rate (ESR) and C-reactive protein (CRP) are within normal limits.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Echocardiogram","MRI head","Ocular ultrasound","CT angiography of the head and neck","Carotid artery ultrasound"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ESeveral cholesterol emboli are visible with the retinal vessels. These have probably arisen from an atheromatous plaque in the carotid artery, embolising to the retina via the ophthalmic artery and producing the transient monocular visual disturbance of \u003Cem\u003Eamaurosis fugax\u003C/em\u003E as described. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst the area of increased redness might be considered a cherry red spot, if this was the case the vision and visual field would be considerable impaired as that diagnosis would imply acute central retinal occlusion. This is an area of haemorrhage not a cherry red spot. A small vessel can be seen running across the bleed. There are never any blood vessels at the macula as it is avascular. There is another small bleed medial to the disc.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EImaging the carotid system will help confirm the diagnosis and guide management, and this is best accomplished in the first instance with \u003Cstrong\u003Ecarotid artery\u003Cem\u003E \u003C/em\u003Eultrasound \u003C/strong\u003Elooking for evidence of stenosis. If that confirmed the presence of stenosis and plaque formation, the a CT angiogram might provide further definition. Further evaluation with an echocardiogram would be appropriate as embolic sources can be present on the mitral and aortic valves as well. An MRI of the head is not going to provide any diagnostic information in this case as the site of the problem is either in a carotid artery or the heart.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["A carotid artery ultrasound should be the initial imaging in cases of amaurosis fugax."],"references":["Varma DD, Cugati S, Lee AW, et al. A review of central retinal artery occlusion: clinical presentation and management. Eye (London, England). 2013;27:688-97.","Hayreh SS. Central retinal artery occlusion. Indian journal of ophthalmology. 2018;66:1684-94."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29946"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"486"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19768"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19768","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19768"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/54de1d0b-9381-4154-94fb-7e9e062230d5.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/54de1d0b-9381-4154-94fb-7e9e062230d5.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":437}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29946","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/29946"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-05-10T10:49:19+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-05-10T10:49:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"486"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"45044"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups"